  "prompt": "Which is the best camera smartphone under 20k?",
  "response": "Okay, recommending the \"best\" camera phone under 20k is tricky because \"best\" is subjective and depends on your priorities. However, I can give you a few top contenders with different strengths, along with reasons why they might be good for you:\n\n**Important Considerations Before Choosing:**\n\n*   **Daylight Photography:** Most phones in this price range do well in good lighting.\n*   **Low-Light Photography:** This is where the differences become more apparent. Look for larger sensors, wider apertures (lower f-number), and good night mode processing.\n*   **Ultrawide Lens:** Do you want a really wide field of view for landscapes or group shots?\n*   **Zoom Capabilities:** Do you need a dedicated telephoto lens or are you okay with digital zoom?\n*   **Video Quality:** What resolution and frame rates do you need? Do you need good stabilization?\n*   **Software Processing:** Different brands have different image processing styles. Some prefer more natural colors, while others boost saturation and contrast.\n*   **Personal Preference:** Ultimately, the best camera is the one you enjoy using and that produces results you like.\n\n**Top Contenders (Keep in mind that prices can fluctuate, so check current prices online):**\n\n1.  **Motorola G84 5G:**\n\n    *   **Pros:**\n        *   **Good Overall Value:** Offers a balance of features for the price.\n        *   **50MP Main Camera with OIS:** Optical Image Stabilization (OIS) helps reduce blur in photos and videos, especially in low light.\n        *   **Ultrawide Lens:** Provides a wider field of view.\n        *   **Clean Software Experience:** Near-stock Android for a smooth and bloat-free experience.\n    *   **Cons:**\n        *   Low light pictures are not that good.\n        *   Ultrawide lens is decent, but not the sharpest.\n\n2.  **Xiaomi Redmi Note 13 5G:**\n\n    *   **Pros:**\n        *   **Good Daylight Performance:** Takes detailed and vibrant photos in good lighting.\n        *   **108MP Main Camera:** Allows for high-resolution images and good cropping potential.\n        *   **Stylish Design:** Often features attractive designs and finishes.\n    *   **Cons:**\n        *   Low-light performance might be okay, but you have to rely on night mode.\n        *   Ultrawide lens is nothing to write home about\n\n3.  **Samsung Galaxy M14 5G / A14 5G:**\n\n    *   **Pros:**\n        *   **Reliable Brand:** Samsung is a well-known and trusted brand.\n        *   **Good Daylight Performance:** Takes decent photos in good lighting.\n        *   **Ultrawide Lens:** Provides a wider field of view.\n        *   **Super Steady Video Recording:** Helps reduce camera shake in videos.\n        *   **Very good battery life**\n    *   **Cons:**\n        *   Low-light performance is decent but nothing special.\n        *   Can be a bit more expensive than other options with similar specs.\n\n4.  **Realme Narzo 60 5G:**\n\n    *   **Pros:**\n        *   **64MP Main Camera:** Good detail and clarity in daylight.\n        *   **Attractive Design:** Often features eye-catching designs.\n        *   **Good Value for Money:** Usually offers competitive specs for the price.\n    *   **Cons:**\n        *   Low-light performance can be inconsistent.\n        *   Ultrawide lens might be missing or not the best quality.\n\n**How to Choose:**\n\n*   **If you prioritize low-light performance with OIS:** The **Motorola G84 5G** is a good choice.\n*   **If you want very good daylight photos:** The **Xiaomi Redmi Note 13 5G**\n*   **If you value a reliable brand and good video stabilization:** The **Samsung Galaxy M14 5G/A14 5G** might be a good option.\n*   **If you're looking for a good value and decent all-around camera:** The **Realme Narzo 60 5G** is worth considering.\n\n**Before you buy:**\n\n*   **Read reviews:** Look for in-depth camera reviews and comparisons on websites like GSMArena, DXOMARK, and YouTube. Pay attention to the reviewers' comments on image quality, low-light performance, and video capabilities.\n*   **Check sample photos:** Look for sample photos taken with the phone in different lighting conditions to get a better idea of its camera performance.\n*   **Visit a store:** If possible, visit a store and try out the phones yourself. Take some test photos and videos to see which one you prefer.\n*   **Consider your needs:** Think about what you'll be using the camera for most often and choose a phone that excels in those areas.\n\nI hope this helps! Let me know if you have any other questions.\n",
